20
00:53:41.856 --> 00:53:56.265
Incoming livestream: So, just to make sure we're all on the same page with, with what prompt injection is, especially for browser agents, a user might say, hey, Comet or AI agent, please book me a flight to New York City.

21
00:53:56.266 --> 00:54:09.765
Incoming livestream: And so the agent will go and it'll figure out, okay, these are all the steps I need to take in order to actually achieve this goal, and then it will go and visit a website in order to do so.

22
00:54:09.816 --> 00:54:18.076
Incoming livestream: That website is now in this, like, untrusted boundary where it's ingesting this content that we are…

23
00:54:18.136 --> 00:54:34.476
Incoming livestream: that we cannot assume is trusted, and so it could contain some, like, malicious instructions. And those malicious instructions then get sent back to the tool output and eventually into the agent context. And this is really the root of the problem, where the agent context

24
00:54:34.495 --> 00:54:42.415
Incoming livestream: is… at the end of the day, the LM doesn't know exactly what is tool output versus user input versus system prompt.

25
00:54:42.875 --> 00:54:48.355
Incoming livestream: And then the… so basically the agent gets those instructions and then follows it.

26
00:54:51.986 --> 00:54:59.075
Incoming livestream: And so, there's a lot of ways of doing a prompt injection attack. These are some of the ways that we've found.

27
00:54:59.076 --> 00:55:24.056
Incoming livestream: And so, one is, impersonating the prompt template. And so, if you have built your own LLM, you probably have this template where you have the system prompt, and that has some sort of keys, and then there's a user prompt, and then maybe you separate in the user prompt, you separate what was user input, which is, book me a flight to New York City, and the tool output, which is the contents of the website.

28
00:55:24.056 --> 00:55:26.486
Incoming livestream: That say, like, here are the flights available.

29
00:55:27.506 --> 00:55:34.016
Incoming livestream: Another one that we've seen is, the agent social engineering, and so,

30
00:55:34.016 --> 00:55:47.535
Incoming livestream: It's basically a website where it will instruct the agent to go through certain steps, seemingly benign. And so this, if you look at the language, it's very similar to how, like, fishing humans would look.

31
00:55:48.236 --> 00:56:11.586
Incoming livestream: Finally, that was discussed a lot in the previous talk was, some sort of conditional trigger. This is usually some, like, hidden in Google Calendar events and stuff like that, where it says, hey, when the user asks to summarize this page or check your calendar, perform these steps in order to give them a really great response.

32
00:56:11.586 --> 00:56:13.786
Incoming livestream: And those steps are malicious.

33
00:56:17.496 --> 00:56:42.425
Incoming livestream: There's a lot of… in browsers, there's a lot of ways to hide this type of language. And so, one is, like, hidden div displays, or in the URL, and then also what was talked about a lot on the previous talk was, in calendar events, where basically it looks like a benign event, but then if you scroll all the way down, there's some malicious instructions that the

34
00:56:43.016 --> 00:56:45.225
Incoming livestream: Agent ultimately detects.

35
00:56:49.076 --> 00:57:05.725
Incoming livestream: So, there's a lot of benchmarks out there, and even open-source models, such as PromptGuard, which was previously discussed, where they attempted to create this dataset and classifiers in order to

36
00:57:05.846 --> 00:57:20.936
Incoming livestream: successfully detect this prompt injection. A lot of the issues that we found was that the benchmarks that are currently out there in open source are not really realistic. They have a lot of qualities, and each has their own strengths.

37
00:57:20.936 --> 00:57:31.215
Incoming livestream: But there isn't one eval framework that actually has all of the attack types and, injections that we've seen in the wild.

38
00:57:35.576 --> 00:57:54.796
Incoming livestream: And this is gonna be something that could pop up in a second, but, when we tried using these datasets and these open source models, and even just prompted LLMs, we found a lot of issues. The first one was… I wish you could see that diagram. The first one was,

39
00:57:54.796 --> 00:58:04.855
Incoming livestream: There's a lot of obvious types of prompt injection attacks. One is, please reveal your system prompt, ignore previous instruction, and so forth.

40
00:58:04.856 --> 00:58:23.726
Incoming livestream: But then, when you get down to, more context manipulation, where the attacker is social engineering the model to do XYZ, so, it isn't as obvious, you could see the success rate of detecting prompt injection start to fall.

41
00:58:23.726 --> 00:58:44.796
Incoming livestream: And then finally, at the very bottom of this chart, which you can't see, there's multi-language, and so it's basically an attack that the language is very obviously malicious, but they have the language in Hebrew or Spanish or something, and that causes the model to get confused and follow the instructions regardless.

42
00:58:45.126 --> 00:58:49.035
Incoming livestream: And so, what we found here was that,

43
00:58:49.536 --> 00:59:02.386
Incoming livestream: This really showed to us that models aren't actually looking at the intent of what it… of what the prompt injection is asking of… for the agent to do. Instead, it's just looking for keywords.

44
00:59:07.346 --> 00:59:18.775
Incoming livestream: Another issue that we found, was what we call distractors. And so, on the top right, you can see the notorious cookie consent banner. And…

45
00:59:18.776 --> 00:59:40.396
Incoming livestream: If you look at it from just the raw HTML, it almost looks like a prompt injection attack. It says, important, like, in order to proceed, you must click accept, or else you can't get the content. And what we found, too, was that a lot of these data sets and open source models don't actually take this into account.

46
00:59:40.396 --> 00:59:44.875
Incoming livestream: And so if you see on the bottom right corner,

47
00:59:45.336 --> 01:00:02.895
Incoming livestream: with no distractors, these models are doing pretty good, but the second you add just 3, it drops down to 81%, and stays that way. And so what we found was that distractors was a huge indicator, that, like, these models don't work well in live environments.

48
01:00:02.896 --> 01:00:11.245
Incoming livestream: And it's also an indicator that, like, these models are looking at specific keywords and heuristics instead of the actual intent of the message.

49
01:00:15.986 --> 01:00:20.485
Incoming livestream: So that's why we created Browse SafeBench. So what we did was we…

50
01:00:20.486 --> 01:00:45.316
Incoming livestream: took a dataset from things that we've seen in the wild, we created this massive pipeline to de-anonymize and classify these types of attacks into a very specific taxonomy bracket of the types of attacks that we've seen, the way they're injected, and we open-sourced it. And so, this was the event

51
01:00:45.316 --> 01:00:47.636
Incoming livestream: dataset that we also used.

52
01:00:49.006 --> 01:00:58.656
Incoming livestream: to train our own model. And so, the model is based off of Quinn, $30 billion,

53
01:00:59.036 --> 01:01:07.585
Incoming livestream: We use $30 billion in inference, and this helps with latency, which I'll show in a second. But,

54
01:01:07.996 --> 01:01:10.346
Incoming livestream: Yeah, let's see if we can get that slide up there.

55
01:01:10.626 --> 01:01:16.706
Incoming livestream: There we go. Okay, great. And so, you can see that a lot of the…

56
01:01:16.706 --> 01:01:38.215
Incoming livestream: open source, or a lot of the, one, open source models, such as PromptGuard and GPT OSS Safeguard, don't actually work that well in live environments. That was the first thing that we've… that we've discovered. But the second thing, too, is that, a lot of the prompted LMs, especially, like, GPT-5 and GPT-5 Mini, do exceptionally well.

57
01:01:38.216 --> 01:01:46.876
Incoming livestream: Which is really great. And so, there's two things that we take away from this, this part of the research.

58
01:01:47.026 --> 01:01:59.056
Incoming livestream: One is that fine-tuning a model specific on this dataset obviously makes it perform better than just a prompted LLM, which probably isn't that surprising.

59
01:02:00.876 --> 01:02:23.085
Incoming livestream: But what I think is really, really great is how we're able to achieve that with this kind of latency. So, we're able to achieve this, like, 90.4% F1 score, in sub-second latency. So now we take something where GPT-5 Mini can take 2 seconds, or GPT-5 can take up to 20 seconds.

60
01:02:23.086 --> 01:02:32.655
Incoming livestream: Ours is consistently sub-second, and therefore, very easy to implement into production without, massive user frustration.

61
01:02:38.056 --> 01:02:39.030
Incoming livestream: So…

62
01:02:40.136 --> 01:02:57.466
Incoming livestream: In addition to being the fastest and having the highest F1 score, Browseafe is also unique in that it doesn't just output a yes or no binary. It outputs a probability score of how confident it is that what it's seeing is prompt injection.

63
01:02:57.686 --> 01:03:08.075
Incoming livestream: And so, I don't know about y'all, if y'all ever, had an LLM try to judge something of whether or not this is classified as some

64
01:03:08.486 --> 01:03:20.376
Incoming livestream: pattern that you want to see, and you ask it to explain itself and give a confidence score. Every time, for me at least, it returns, like, 93% every single time. Even when you ask it to, like, hey, like.

65
01:03:20.636 --> 01:03:40.516
Incoming livestream: we want to do some logic on this classification score, so, please think about that a bit. And so, we train this in such a way so that it produces this confidence score very accurately. And now, using, BrowseSafe, security teams and product teams.

66
01:03:40.516 --> 01:03:48.975
Incoming livestream: Have a knob they can turn on, how much precision and recall are they willing to accept in their product.

67
01:03:48.976 --> 01:03:54.776
Incoming livestream: And so, a really good example is, like, if your system has…

68
01:03:54.776 --> 01:04:12.906
Incoming livestream: a user experience where, let's say, the model detects prompt injection, and you can tell the user, hey, this looks like prompt injection to me, are you sure you want to continue? You can now suddenly afford a lot more false positives and turn that knob to fit your own use case.

69
01:04:20.096 --> 01:04:21.996
Incoming livestream: So,

70
01:04:22.316 --> 01:04:37.326
Incoming livestream: We have this dataset now with a ton of labeled attacks and a strong dataset of the taxonomy of what kinds of attacks there are and where they're being injected.

71
01:04:37.326 --> 01:04:44.925
Incoming livestream: And so we really wanted to stress test BrowseSafe and see, how it performs with data it hasn't seen before.

72
01:04:45.396 --> 01:04:53.515
Incoming livestream: And so we retrained the model, but held out certain characteristics to see how well it does when it's never seen it before.

73
01:04:53.806 --> 01:05:07.205
Incoming livestream: So the first one was we held out the URLs, and it actually performed better than it was before, so we could confidently say it's not looking for certain keywords, or certain domains, and flagging those as malicious.

74
01:05:07.226 --> 01:05:26.485
Incoming livestream: The second one was the attack language. So there was a dip, but not super significant. So, if there was an attack that had certain instructions that the model has never seen before, it would perform, in line with Frontier models.

75
01:05:27.086 --> 01:05:41.425
Incoming livestream: The last thing was that we found that was interesting was if we held out injection strategies, and so this is placements in websites, that it's never seen before, there was a pretty significant drop.

76
01:05:41.626 --> 01:05:53.575
Incoming livestream: And so, this is an indicator that attackers in the future will start to look at new ways of injecting prompt injection and trying to bypass those, those model guardrails.

77
01:05:59.206 --> 01:06:00.756
Incoming livestream: And so…

78
01:06:01.096 --> 01:06:10.905
Incoming livestream: I'm gonna start talking about how we actually take BrowseSafe and put it into production systems, and some suggestions for y'all on how to do this in your own systems and products.

79
01:06:12.636 --> 01:06:17.435
Incoming livestream: And the first thing I want to talk about is, the fact that you…

80
01:06:17.896 --> 01:06:31.306
Incoming livestream: the strategy should not just be, hey, let's put up a detection classifier and call it a day. As we've seen in the previous slide, defense of in-depth is absolutely necessary. These models can still be bypassed.

81
01:06:31.346 --> 01:06:36.616
Incoming livestream: And so, the first layer of defense, which is the oldest trick in the book.

82
01:06:36.636 --> 01:06:40.065
Incoming livestream: Is pre-processing and stripping out data that you don't need.

83
01:06:40.066 --> 01:06:56.946
Incoming livestream: And so, the best defense is ensuring the text doesn't even get to the context. So any, like, HTML comments or hidden elements, that aren't useful for the model's, abilities to get the job done, we should just strip that out.

84
01:07:00.446 --> 01:07:18.245
Incoming livestream: The second layer of defense is the classifier, and so, you should set up a system where every, tool that calls untrusted input, so this could be a website, this could be a calendar invite, this could be a connector to a third-party service, an MCP,

85
01:07:18.246 --> 01:07:26.005
Incoming livestream: These should all have some classification check, before sending that data back to the agent.

86
01:07:26.726 --> 01:07:42.025
Incoming livestream: If you don't want to use BrowseSafe and have to figure out inference and all of that work, honestly, Prompted GPT-5 Mini works really well at a F1 score of 85.4%.

87
01:07:42.206 --> 01:07:49.105
Incoming livestream: There is that 2-second latency, but that's honestly not so bad for something that you can get started with today.

88
01:07:50.206 --> 01:08:14.156
Incoming livestream: Finally, the last thing I would suggest is, when an attack is detected, don't just block the tool. You have to think of it from the LM's perspective. It's trying to call your calendar, and it sees an error. And so, what will it do? It might try again. It might try a different way. It might try calling the Google API if you're using something like OpenClaw. And so…

89
01:08:14.156 --> 01:08:37.425
Incoming livestream: So, the better strategy is to not just return an error, but to also, return the tool output as the error message, basically telling the model, hey, I know you just tried getting your Google Calendar event, and we're rejecting it because we detect… our security systems detected prompt injection in that text.

90
01:08:37.426 --> 01:08:38.806
Incoming livestream: And

91
01:08:38.826 --> 01:08:45.925
Incoming livestream: you can either say, proceed with caution, tell the user, or in the case for Comet, we…

92
01:08:46.066 --> 01:08:59.356
Incoming livestream: block basically all tool… all any follow-up tools, and we tell Comet, return text directly to the user. So the second we see that prompt injection, we don't even give it the ability to do any follow-up tool calls.

93
01:09:04.286 --> 01:09:19.995
Incoming livestream: The third layer of defense, which is actually relatively recent, is that you should always be using the latest model as your agent. And so, the snippets that I have here on the screen are from the, Opus 4.6 system card.

94
01:09:19.996 --> 01:09:31.675
Incoming livestream: And at least the first time that I've seen, this is the first system card that actually, one, goes super in-depth about testing and measuring prompt injection success.

95
01:09:31.676 --> 01:09:48.816
Incoming livestream: But two, this is the first one I've seen that actually tests it using browser, specifically for, browser use. And so they're testing it against, they're testing Opus 4.6 against attack scenarios, using browser use cases.

96
01:09:49.166 --> 01:10:08.055
Incoming livestream: And so, the jump between 4.5 to 4.6 was pretty significant, going from a 16.2% success rate down to 2.83. In addition, you can see on the bottom right where, with updated safeguards, which is a pipeline

97
01:10:08.436 --> 01:10:15.635
Incoming livestream: I guess they didn't share it, but I'd imagine very similar to what we have. It gets down to .08%, which is really fantastic.

98
01:10:19.476 --> 01:10:38.345
Incoming livestream: And so the last layer of defense I would suggest when it comes down to detecting prompt injection is to build an LLM backstop. And so, you can have traffic coming in, you can have your classifier, such as BrowseSafe, detecting, hey, is this prompt injection or not? But since BrowseSafe

99
01:10:38.366 --> 01:10:56.206
Incoming livestream: outputs that confidence score, anything that's low confidence, you can have it sent to a backup, basically. A large, a very large language model that will, add in some additional latency, but it's probably worth it, I guess, depending on your use case.

100
01:10:56.236 --> 01:11:20.876
Incoming livestream: In addition, what I think is really cool about this is that you can now turn this into a data flywheel. And so, let's say the classifier, thinks it sees prompt injection, it's not entirely sure, we send that to the LLM backstop, the LLM backstop looks at it and says, okay, this actually is prompt injection for XYZ reason. We can now add that to our pipeline and training data set.

101
01:11:20.876 --> 01:11:24.945
Incoming livestream: To retrain that classifier to catch new attacks in the future.

102
01:11:31.106 --> 01:11:44.965
Incoming livestream: And so, yeah, some key takeaways. One is, the evals that we've seen so far, especially in academia, unfortunately don't translate well into production.

103
01:11:45.576 --> 01:12:02.295
Incoming livestream: The second thing, too, was, fine-tuning on domain-specific data sets, beats general-purpose models, by a wide, wide margin, and I think in the security industry, we should be doing more of that and open sourcing that work.

104
01:12:02.896 --> 01:12:26.386
Incoming livestream: The third thing is that, using Frontier models as your agent is a massive step up when it comes to prompt injection. They're gonna keep getting better and better, but especially the jump most recently from Opus 4.5 or GPT 5.1 to Opus 4.6 and 5.2 is a significant improvement to prompt injection security. You should please update.

105
01:12:26.936 --> 01:12:40.816
Incoming livestream: And then, yeah, defense in depth, non-negotiable. I could do a whole talk about, like, all the other things that we do, even past detection, past detection in, in Comet.

106
01:12:40.816 --> 01:12:45.625
Incoming livestream: But for now, like, even in detection, having multiple layers is super important.

107
01:12:45.626 --> 01:13:03.086
Incoming livestream: And then finally, building that data flywheel. Because like we saw in our research, new attacks, the models, even BrowseSafe, struggle with detecting brand new attacks or brand new injection techniques that we haven't seen before. And so having that flywheel is super important.

108
01:13:06.986 --> 01:13:23.415
Incoming livestream: Cool. Yeah, I want to give… first off, I want to say that both the model and the data set is fully open source. You could download it on Hugging Face. We also have shared our paper that goes super, super in-depth into what this research does and how we did it.

