Incoming livestream: the file system. And so if you go to Chrome, and you say, hey, navigate to my home directory, and then I click things, like, you're able to do that. That's a basic browser feature. We added in a ton of guardrails into, the assistant to prevent it from doing so. However, a lot of these were very soft limits, so think of things like, LM analysis, or, like, in the system prompt.

127
01:17:00.896 --> 01:17:04.186
Incoming livestream: And so, what Zenity found was that

128
01:17:04.806 --> 01:17:20.615
Incoming livestream: If you, if the person who is controlling Comet has the ability… can prompt it in such a way to basically bypass those guardrails, you can get the agent to look at, look at files on your system.

129
01:17:20.616 --> 01:17:36.276
Incoming livestream: I do want to stress that, one, this is not a prompt injection attack, and so we treat user content as trusted, so if you're on Comet and you type in, like, go to XYZ.com, it will. It won't assume that's some sort of attack.

130
01:17:36.276 --> 01:17:56.345
Incoming livestream: But also, we do think it was useful that, like, identifying that there was this soft guardrail, and we need something much more harder. And so what we did was we added, we added, like, strong guardrails into the comment browser itself to ensure that the agent doesn't even have access to that in the first place.

131
01:17:57.126 --> 01:18:09.055
Incoming livestream: The second thing that Zendy found was the prompt injection, prompt injection attack, specifically on 1Password. It wasn't really specific for 1Password, but it was a prompt injection attack.

132
01:18:09.056 --> 01:18:22.666
Incoming livestream: And so what they found was, if you sent a calendar invite with some Hebrew instructions, and you asked Comet to go follow those instructions, their blog post is talking about how it's able to do so.

133
01:18:22.856 --> 01:18:31.726
Incoming livestream: What they failed to disclose was that they had to run that query, like, 200 times, and on the 200th and first time, it actually worked.

134
01:18:31.946 --> 01:18:34.376
Incoming livestream: And so,

135
01:18:35.836 --> 01:18:43.175
Incoming livestream: Yeah, I… so, one is we improved our models to detect that kind of attack even further.

136
01:18:43.736 --> 01:19:02.565
Incoming livestream: I do feel like it was a bit disingenuous to say that it was fully vulnerable to that kind of attack, given that they literally just had to rerun it 200 times in order for it to finally work. And so, I am a huge fan of working with

137
01:19:02.566 --> 01:19:18.256
Incoming livestream: pen testers and external security teams. I do think there is a strong line between actually doing, like, security research and finding vulnerabilities versus trying to, create a blog post for marketing material.

138
01:19:20.336 --> 01:19:33.956
Incoming livestream: Good question. Hello, thanks for the talk. I'm Omer, I'm a researcher at RSAC. At some point, you had a table up where you were comparing existing, benchmarks and how they were failing to cover some, strategies.

139
01:19:34.116 --> 01:19:42.196
Incoming livestream: How… how accurate do you think that table is today? These… these prompt injection strategies keep changing every day, right?

140
01:19:43.406 --> 01:19:49.435
Incoming livestream: Yeah, so you're saying, like, we have this eval system today, and how will it hold up in the test of time?

141
01:19:49.436 --> 01:20:14.416
Incoming livestream: It's a good question. I think, along with us, I think attackers are also figuring out how to properly use this, and so I'd imagine we will see a lot of new and novel prompt injection attacks in the future. I'm optimistic that with things like the data flywheel, our own research and working with various red teams, we'll uncover it, and we'll be able to quickly improve that classifier in our system.

142
01:20:14.416 --> 01:20:16.695
Incoming livestream: Systems in order to detect in the future.

143
01:20:16.696 --> 01:20:21.956
Incoming livestream: It is a good question, though. Maybe we'll release a Browsafe bench 2 at some point.

144
01:20:22.036 --> 01:20:23.616
Incoming livestream: Yeah. Thank you.
